A programmer wants to check whether a prediction program makes more errors for one group than another. The following code counts errors for group `"A"`.

```java
String[] group = {"A", "B", "A", "A", "B"};
boolean[] predicted = {true, true, false, true, false};
boolean[] actual = {true, false, true, true, false};
int errors = 0;

for (int i = 0; i < group.length; i++)
{
    if (group[i].equals("A") && predicted[i] != actual[i])
    {
        errors++;
    }
}
```

What is the value of `errors` after the code runs?

A programmer writes the following code to compare average wait times for two groups in a data set.

```java
int[] times = {12, 18, 20, 30, 16, 28};
String[] groups = {"A", "B", "A", "B", "A", "B"};
int sumA = 0;
int sumB = 0;

for (int i = 0; i < times.length; i++)
{
    if (groups[i].equals("A"))
    {
        sumA += times[i];
    }
    else
    {
        sumB += times[i];
    }
}

System.out.println(sumA / times.length);
System.out.println(sumB / times.length);
```

Which of the following best describes the ethical concern with using this output to make a decision?
